Next, iterate through the filtered log entries to find the initial one, which should be marked as "ENTRY". This indicates the start of a new transaction. Once you've identified the initial entry, extract the timestamp associated with it. For each subsequent log entry (marked as "EXIT"), subtract the corresponding timestamp from the initial timestamp to determine the delay in milliseconds. Finally, divide the accumulated delay by 60000 (the number of milliseconds in a minute) to obtain the total minutes of delay.


```java
public void getTotalDelay() {
    // Get all log entries
    List<LogEntry> logEntries = SqlStatementLogger.getLogEntries();

    // Filter log entries based on the tag name "SQL"
    List<LogEntry> sqlLogs = logEntries.stream()
       .filter(log -> log.getTag().equals("SQL"))
       .collect(Collectors.toList());

    long initialTimestamp = -1;
    long delayTotalMs = 0;

    // Find the initial log entry
    for (LogEntry log : sqlLogs) {
        if (log.getMessage().contains("ENTRY")) {
            initialTimestamp = log.getTimestamp();
            break;
        }
    }

    // Calculate delay for each exit log entry
